Weapons do not break or require repair. Each weapon has stats: Might
(damage bonus), Hit (accuracy bonus), Crit (critical rate bonus), Weight
(reduces effective SPD if higher than unit's STR), and Range (1 for
melee, 2 for ranged, 1--2 for some magic).

7.3 Accessories

Accessories provide passive stat bonuses and sometimes unique effects.
Examples: Shield Ring (+3 DEF), Speed Ring (+3 SPD), Critical Band (+15
Crit), Renewal Ring (heal 10% HP per turn), Boots (+1 MOV). Accessories
come in common, uncommon, and rare tiers with corresponding stat
magnitudes.

7.4 Consumables

Consumables are single-use items found as loot or purchased: Vulnerary
(heal 10 HP), Elixir (heal to full), Promotion Item (required for
promotion), Stat Boosters (permanently increase one stat by 1--2), Skill
Scroll (grants an equipped skill). Consumables are lost at end of run.

8\. Roguelike Systems

8.1 Randomization

The following elements are randomized each run:

-   Node map paths (branching structure within each Act)

-   Battle maps (generated from templates with randomized terrain
    placement)

-   Enemy compositions (drawn from level-appropriate pools per Act)

-   Recruited unit stats (class growths rolled within ranges at
    recruitment)

-   Shop inventories (random selection from tier-appropriate item pools)

-   Loot drops (weapons, accessories, skill scrolls, consumables from
    tiered pools)

-   Level-up stat gains (each stat rolls against growth rate
    independently)

-   Elite/miniboss encounters (drawn from a pool, each with unique
    mechanics)

-   Fog of war and terrain modifiers (random chance per map)

-   Recruit event availability and which characters appear

8.2 Loot & Rewards

After each battle, the player is presented with a choice of loot.
Standard battles offer a choice of 1 from 3 random items. Elite battles
offer a choice of 2 from 4 items of higher quality. Boss battles grant a
guaranteed powerful reward plus meta-progression currency. Loot pools
scale by Act: Act 1 primarily offers Iron-tier gear and common
accessories; Act 2 introduces Steel-tier and uncommon accessories; Act 3
features Silver-tier and rare accessories; Post-Act and Bosses can drop
Legendary items.

8.3 Recruitment

Units are recruited during runs through two mechanisms:

-   **Recruit Event Nodes:** On the node map, recruit events are combat
    maps featuring a green NPC ally. The Lord must move adjacent to the
    NPC and use the Talk action to recruit them. The NPC fights with
    basic defensive AI and is not suicidal, but enemies may target them.
    If the NPC falls before recruitment, they are lost for this run.

-   **Mid-Battle Recruits:** Occasionally, a green NPC will appear on a
    standard battle map. Same recruitment mechanic. This is rarer and
    adds a secondary objective to the battle.

Recruited units are generated with: a random class (from the player's
unlocked class pool), a level appropriate to the current Act, randomized
stats based on class growths, a basic weapon appropriate to their class,
and no equipped skills (must be given Skill Scrolls).

8.4 Gold Economy

Gold is earned from battles (base amount + bonuses for performance),
selling unwanted loot, and sometimes from events. Gold is spent at shops
on weapons, accessories, consumables, skill scrolls, and promotion
items. Gold does not persist between runs. The economy should be tuned
so that players must make meaningful choices about what to buy rather
than purchasing everything.

9\. Meta-Progression

9.1 Meta-Currency

Runs award a meta-currency (working name: Renown) based on progress.
Renown is earned from: defeating bosses (large amounts), completing
Acts, total enemies defeated, and bonus objectives. Even failed runs
earn Renown proportional to progress. Renown is spent at the Home Base
between runs.

9.2 Home Base

The Home Base is the persistent hub between runs. It contains upgrade
stations where Renown is spent:

9.2.1 Lord Upgrades

-   Improve Lord's base growth rates (e.g., +5% STR growth, capped)

-   Improve Lord's starting base stats (+1 STR, +1 SPD, etc., capped)

-   Unlock additional weapon proficiencies for the Lord

-   Upgrade weapon proficiencies to Mastery

-   Unlock and customize starting skills (innate and equipped)

-   Unlock starting weapons (begin runs with better gear)

-   Unlock alternative Lord classes / promotion paths

9.2.2 Class & Recruit Upgrades

-   Unlock new classes for the recruitment pool

-   Improve generic recruit base stats and growth rate ranges

-   Unlock innate skills for base classes

-   Unlock innate skills for promoted classes

-   Increase equipped skill slot count (1 → 2 → 3)

-   Unlock new weapon proficiencies for classes

9.2.3 Special Character Unlocks

Special Characters are unique named units with fixed personal growth
rates and sometimes unique class trees. They are unlocked via
meta-progression and then appear in the recruitment pool during runs.
Unlike generic recruits, Special Characters retain their identity across
runs (same name, appearance, personal skill) but must still be recruited
each run. They start each run fresh but benefit from any class-level
meta-upgrades.

9.2.4 General Upgrades

-   Increase starting gold

-   Better starting shop inventories

-   Increase loot drop quality

-   Unlock additional node map events

-   NPC warriors (starting allies in early battles) get improved stats

9.3 Progression Balance Philosophy

Meta-progression should make early Acts feel smoother and open new
strategic options, but should never trivialize the late game. The
strongest upgrades (starting stats, growth rates) are capped to prevent
overpowering. The most impactful unlocks are lateral (new classes, new
Lords, new Special Characters) rather than strictly vertical. A fully
upgraded Lord with a team of clerics should still lose to Act 3 content
because maps demand multiple competent combat units through split-path
objectives and multi-front battles.

