11\. Enemy & Boss Design

11.1 Enemy Scaling

Enemies scale by Act. Each Act has a pool of enemy unit types at
appropriate levels with appropriate equipment:

  ---------- --------------- --------------- ------------------------------
  **Act**    **Enemy Level   **Equipment     **Class Variety**
             Range**         Tier**          

  Act 1      1--5            Iron            Fighters, Soldiers, Archers,
                                             Brigands

  Act 2      5--12           Iron/Steel      Above + Cavaliers, Mages,
                                             Knights, Mercenaries

  Act 3      12--18          Steel/Silver    Above + Swordmasters, Snipers,
                                             Sages, Generals, Promoted
                                             enemies

  Post-Act   16--20          Silver          Fully promoted enemies with
                                             skills
  ---------- --------------- --------------- ------------------------------

11.2 Elite Enemies (Minibosses)

Elites are named enemies with higher stats, unique skills, and sometimes
unique AI behaviors. They are drawn randomly from a pool. Examples: a
General with Pavise (chance to halve damage) who turtles behind a wall
of soldiers; an Assassin with Lethality (chance of instant kill) who
targets your weakest unit; a Sage with Bolting (long-range magic) who
must be reached through a gauntlet.

11.3 Act Bosses

Act Bosses are fixed (non-random) encounters designed to be learnable.
Each has a unique map layout, reinforcement pattern, and boss mechanics.
They are the primary difficulty gates and the source of the best
rewards. Boss design should test different tactical skills: Act 1 Boss
tests basic weapon triangle and positioning; Act 2 Boss tests
multi-front management and objective prioritization; Act 3 Boss tests
full team coordination with promoted enemies and boss mechanics.

11.4 Final Boss

The Final Boss is a multi-phase encounter on a large map. It should
require the player's full 6-unit roster operating at peak effectiveness.
The Final Boss has multiple phases, reinforcements, and unique mechanics
that test mastery of all game systems.

12\. Asset Requirements

12.1 Art Assets

12.1.1 Character Sprites (Map View)

Top-down or 3/4 view sprites for the game map. Each class needs: idle
animation (2 frames), walk animation (4 frames, 4 directions), and a
selected/highlighted state. At minimum 15--20 class sprite sets are
needed. Resolution: 32x32 pixels per frame recommended (or 16x16 for a
more retro feel). Palette: define a consistent 32-color master palette.
Each faction (player, enemy, NPC) uses color-swapped variants of the
same sprites.

12.1.2 Character Sprites (Battle View)

Side-view sprites for combat animations. Each class needs: idle (2
frames), attack (4--6 frames), hit/damage (2 frames), dodge (2--4
frames), critical attack (6--8 frames), and defeat/death (4 frames).
These are larger sprites: 64x64 or 96x96 recommended. This is the most
art-intensive requirement. For MVP, consider using minimal battle
animations (attack flash + damage number) and adding full animations
later.

12.1.3 Portraits

Character portraits for dialogue, recruitment, and stat screens. Lords
and Special Characters need unique portraits. Generic recruits can share
class-based portraits with color variations. Resolution: 96x96 or
128x128. This is a strong candidate for AI image generation --- generate
portraits in a consistent pixel art style, then manually clean up for
consistency.

12.1.4 Map Tilesets

Tile-based map graphics for 3--4 biome types (grassland/plains,
castle/fortress, cave/dungeon, forest). Each biome needs: base terrain
tiles, terrain features (trees, rocks, walls, water, bridges), objective
tiles (throne, gate, chest), and decorative elements. Standard tilesets
from itch.io or OpenGameArt are recommended as a starting point.

12.1.5 UI Elements

Menu backgrounds, stat screen layout, health bars, XP bar,
weapon/skill/item icons, cursor sprites, tile highlights (movement
range, attack range, selected), damage numbers, level-up screen, node
map graphics, and shop interface. A clean pixel-art UI kit is essential.

12.1.6 Effects

Visual effects for: weapon attacks (slash, pierce, impact), magic (fire,
lightning, wind, light, dark), healing (staff glow), critical hit flash,
level-up sparkle, promotion transformation, and status effects. These
can be simple sprite animations: 4--8 frames each.

12.2 Sound Assets

12.2.1 Sound Effects

Essential sound effects: menu cursor move, menu select, menu cancel,
attack hit (physical), attack hit (magical), critical hit, miss/dodge,
healing, level up jingle, unit defeated, gold received, item obtained,
skill activated, chapter clear fanfare, game over sting, node map
selection, and shop purchase. Free resources: OpenGameArt.org,
Freesound.org, or retro-style SFX generators like sfxr/jsfxr.

12.2.2 Music

Minimum music tracks needed: title screen theme, home base theme, node
map theme, standard battle theme, boss battle theme, final boss theme,
victory fanfare, game over theme, and recruitment/event theme. Chiptune
or orchestral-chip hybrid (Octopath Traveler style) fits the aesthetic.
AI music generation tools (Suno, Udio) or royalty-free retro game music
packs are viable options.

12.3 Asset Pipeline Recommendations

For practical development:

-   Use placeholder art during prototyping (colored rectangles, simple
    shapes).

-   Source tilesets from free asset packs on itch.io (many excellent
    SNES-style RPG tilesets exist).

-   Use AI image generation for portraits and concept art, with manual
    cleanup in Aseprite or Piskel.

-   For character sprites, consider hiring a pixel artist for the core
    set (15--20 classes) or using free sprite packs as a foundation.

-   Sound effects can be generated with jsfxr for retro-style SFX.

-   Music should be sourced from royalty-free packs or commissioned
    separately.

The highest-priority art for MVP is: map tilesets (1 biome), character
map sprites (5--6 classes), basic UI, and placeholder battle animations.

